      <text>Proving the set of natural numbers using mathematical induction</text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>Consider the following proposition, then fill in the blanks to complete the proof outlined below it.</p>

<br>

<p><strong>Proposition:</strong> Show that by mathematical induction that &nbsp; \(\displaystyle  \sum_{k=1}^{n} k^2 = \frac{n(n+1)(2n+1)}{6}\)</p>
<p><em>Note: "LHS" means Left Hand Side and "RHS" means Right Hand Side.</em></p>
<p><em>We also use the notation, &nbsp; \( \sum_{k=1}^{n} k^2 = 1^2 + 2^2 + 3^2 + \cdots + n^2 \)</em></p>

<br>

<p><strong>Proof by induction:</strong></p>
<p>Define \(P(n)\) to be the statement of the proposition, that: \(\displaystyle  \sum_{k=1}^{n} k^2 = \frac{n(n+1)(2n+1)}{6} \)</p>

<p><b>Step 1:</b> Base case.</p>
<p>For \(n = 1\), we have</p>

<p style="margin-left:30px">LHS: \(\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^{n} k^2 =\) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]]</p>
<p>[[feedback:prt1]]</p> 

<p style="margin-left:30px">RHS: \( \frac{n(n+1)(2n+1)}{6}=\) [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]]</p>
<p>[[feedback:prt2]]</p>

<p>Since these are equal, \( P(1) \) is [[input:ans3]] [[validation:ans3]]</p>
<p>[[feedback:prt3]]</p>

<br>

<p><b>Step 2:</b> Induction step.</p>
<p>Assume \(P(n)\) is true, which means that \( \sum_{k=1}^{n} k^2 = \frac{n(n+1)(2n+1)}{6} \)
<br>This is called the <b>induction hypothesis</b>.</p>
<p>We then need to show \( P(n+1) \) is true.</p>

<br>

<p>\(P(n+1): \displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^{n+1} k^2 = \sum_{k=1}^{n} k^2 \) + [[input:ans4]] [[validation:ans4]]</p>
<p style="margin-left:131px">\(=\) [[input:ans5]] [[validation:ans5]] &nbsp; (using the induction hypothesis)</p>
<p style="margin-left:131px">\(= (n+1) \times ( \) [[input:ans5b]] \()\) [[validation:ans5b]] &nbsp; (factorizing out the common term)</p>
<p style="margin-left:131px">\(= (n+1)(n+2) \times ( \) [[input:ans5c]] \()\) [[validation:ans5c]] &nbsp; (factorising the quadratic)</p>
<p style="margin-left:131px">\(=\) [[input:ans5d]] [[validation:ans5d]] &nbsp; (writing in the form of the RHS of \(P(n+1)\))</p>
<p>[[feedback:prt4]]</p>

<p>So, \(P(n+1)\) is [[input:ans6]] [[validation:ans6]] [[feedback:prt5]]</p>

<br>

<p>Therefore, by the Principle of Mathematical Induction, we have \( \displaystyle  \sum_{k=1}^{n} k^2 = \frac{n(n+1)(2n+1)}{6}\)</p>]]></text>
